EBOLA VIRUS DISEASE - CENTRAL AFRICA: ABSENCE FROM CENTRAL AFRICAN REPUBLIC
***************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 2 Sep 2014
Source: Star Africa [in French, trans. Mod.PB, edited]
http://fr.starafrica.com/actualites/le-directeur-de-linstitut-pasteur-de-bangui-explique-les-raisons-de-labsence-debola-en-rca.html


[NB: this report formed a part of: Ebola virus disease - West Africa (148): CDC, WHO, Nigeria, Liberia, more 20140903.2743746]

The Ebola virus is circulating in Central African wildlife, but conditions have perhaps not been met for an epidemic to occur, the director of the Pasteur Institute of Bangui, Emmanuel Nakoune Yandoko, said on Monday [1 Sep 2014]. For years, his institute has conducted research to understand why every year there is an outbreak of Ebola virus in the sub-region but not in the Central African Republic [CAR].

For him, the presence of antibodies in CAR citizens is preventing manifestation of Ebola in the country. "Through this study, we found that 13 per cent of the Pygmies had antibodies against Ebola virus, and 10 per cent of the non-Pygmy population living in the area also had antibodies." To answer the question of whether Ebola virus was circulating in CAR, rats, bats, monkeys and cane rats were captured and tested, and evidence of infection was found in the livers of these animals.

Prime minister Mahamat Kamoun said: "It is time to be alert to this serious outbreak of Ebola rampant in Africa."

